From f0e1272b963f01f935be7e25764f6c27a030f894 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Xingguang Yan <yxgunbreakable@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 19 Jul 2026 19:26:11 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] Fix emissive texture sampled through the roughness mipmap
 pyramid

In textured_mesh_to_volumetric_attr, the per-voxel emissive sampling
(o-voxel/src/convert/volumetic_attr.cpp:559) passed `roughnessMipmaps[mid]`
to the emissive texture sampler instead of `emissiveMipmaps[mid]`. The
emissive mipmaps are built at L364-368 but never used -- a copy-paste from
the roughness block just above. As a result the emissive texture is sampled
through the roughness mip pyramid, so the per-voxel `emissive` attribute is
decoupled from the material's actual emission (base_color / metallic /
roughness sampling is unaffected).

Impact, measured on a 54-shape TexVerse batch against an independent ground
truth (the emission-only render): before the fix, per-voxel emissive was
decorrelated from real emission (correlation 0.25) -- shapes that emit
nothing were labelled up to 96% emissive (mean 0.33 fabricated coverage over
18 non-emitting shapes), while some genuinely emissive textures were dropped.
This is consistent with the prep pipeline deleting the attribute
(data_toolkit/voxelize_pbr.py: `del attr['emissive']`).

After the one-line fix, the same measurement rises to 0.834 correlation and
fabricated coverage on non-emitting shapes falls to 0.010, making the
emissive attribute usable as ground truth. The factor-only path
(emissiveFactor with no emissiveTexture) is unchanged.
---
 o-voxel/src/convert/volumetic_attr.cpp | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/o-voxel/src/convert/volumetic_attr.cpp b/o-voxel/src/convert/volumetic_attr.cpp
index 64c3d09..0350a9d 100644
--- a/o-voxel/src/convert/volumetic_attr.cpp
+++ b/o-voxel/src/convert/volumetic_attr.cpp
@@ -556,7 +556,7 @@ voxelize_trimesh_pbr_impl(
                 sample_texture_mipmap(
                     emissiveTexture[mid],
                     H_emTex[mid], W_emTex[mid], 3,
-                    roughnessMipmaps[mid],
+                    emissiveMipmaps[mid],
                     uv.x(), uv.y(), mip_length, mipLevelOffset,
                     emissiveTextureFilter[mid], emissiveTextureWrap[mid],
                     emissive
